# 🚀 Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)

## 🔥 Definition (simple)

> **“Don’t force a class to implement methods it doesn’t need.”**

---

## ❌ BAD DESIGN (Violation of ISP)

### 👇 Suppose you design one big interface:

```java
interface Worker {
    void work();
    void eat();
}
```

Now you have 2 classes:

```java
class Human implements Worker {
    public void work() {
        System.out.println("Human working");
    }

    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Human eating");
    }
}
```

```java
class Robot implements Worker {
    public void work() {
        System.out.println("Robot working");
    }

    public void eat() {
        // ❌ Problem: Robot doesn't eat!
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Robot doesn't eat");
    }
}
```

---

## 💥 Problem here

* Robot is **forced** to implement `eat()`
* But robot **doesn't need it**
* You had to write **dummy / exception code**

👉 This is **bad design**

---

# ✅ GOOD DESIGN (Follow ISP)

## 🔧 Split interface into smaller ones

```java
interface Workable {
    void work();
}

interface Eatable {
    void eat();
}
```

---

## 👇 Now implement properly

```java
class Human implements Workable, Eatable {
    public void work() {
        System.out.println("Human working");
    }

    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Human eating");
    }
}
```

```java
class Robot implements Workable {
    public void work() {
        System.out.println("Robot working");
    }
}
```

---

## 🎯 Benefits

* No unnecessary methods
* Clean code
* No exceptions / dummy logic
* Flexible system

